                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d382">
                <head>No. 382.<lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Evarts</persName> to Mr. <persName
                            type="to">Comly</persName>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>,<lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1880-03-05">
                            <hi rend="italic">March</hi> 5, 1880</date>.</dateline>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 55.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: Your dispatch. No. 91, of the 16th ultimo, in
                    which you report your action, together with that of Mr. Consular-Agent Spencer,
                    in the <pb facs="0701" n="601" xml:id="pg_601"/> matter of the illegal arrest
                    and taxation of one Patrick Quinn, a citizen of the United States, has been
                    received, as well as the several inclosures, being the correspondence had in
                    relation thereto, and read with interest and close attention, and it gives me
                    pleasure to say that your course and that of Mr. Spencer, in the premises, meets
                    with entire approval.</p>
                <p>I am, &amp;c.,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>WM. M. EVARTS.</signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
